column61: Lila Deinhammer (pretrial prosecution trial attorney) shows an impressive knowledge of both the applicable law and facts of the case. It was evident that she understood the nuances of existing precedent in such a way that allowed her to creatively and swiftly respond to judge’s questions during her argument. Her ability to distinguish the facts of her case with existing precedent demonstrated a level of sophistication beyond her years.

column61: All attorneys did a GREAT job! Don’t be afraid to slow down during witness questioning if you speak quickly, as it gives the listener time to process, and don’t be afraid to project if you speak softer. You all knew the law well, made effective objections and gave well reasoned responses and arguments. Truly impressive!!

column40: Prosecution Witness Imari Rodriguez (First Assistant Director)
column50: Don’t be afraid of pausing, gathering yourself, and continuing to speak. I understand time constraints of competition but the more you practice doing that, the shorter your pauses will be and the easier it will be to get back on track.
column61:
Representatives of the State of California:

Great job all around. Public speaking is hard but the more you do it the better you get and it’s very clear that you all incredibly comfortable projecting and speaking publicly.

The people’s case was a bit of an uphill battle but you all crushed it.

Counsel for the Defendant:

Incredible defense. You all know the facts and the best arguments for your client. I appreciated the focus each of you gave to the prior testimony and questions asked by the People.

Your case in chief was solid and brought home by an excellent closing argument. You kept it concise on cross and your directs were solid. 

I am truly impressed by each one of you. Keep up the great work!

column44: Prosecution Witness Imari Rodriguez (First Assistant Director)
